  "doc_id": "31311",
  "text": "African rainforests are already close to the hydrological limits of closed canopy forest [CITATION_1] , and their resilience to increases in water stress is uncertain, particularly given that drier conditions would also heighten the risk of fire [CITATION_2] . Drier periods in the last two to three millennia led some forests to become more open, more fire-prone and less carbon-dense [CITATION_3] . It is difficult to judge whether the magnitude of MCWD 100 change projected here would drive this scale of ecological change. The average MCWD 100 for humid tropical forests in Africa is approximately 2300 mm month [CITATION_4] , and regions with MCWD 100 below 2400 mm month 21 are generally inhabited by other types of forest or savanna [CITATION_5] . Therefore, the order of magnitude of the anomalies projected by some AO-PPE models after 28C of global warming could have a large impact: at 38C one model exhibits a decrease greater than 100 mm month",
